      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-warmGray">
        <p class="text-xl leading-relaxed mb-6">
          When a surgeon asks about <a
            href="/methods/endomidface-direct-vision"
            class="text-accent-600 hover:text-accent-700 underline">ENDOMIDFACE® by Direct Vision</a
          >, one of the first questions is often: <em
            >"But isn't endoscopic surgery more advanced?"</em
          >
        </p>

        <p class="mb-6">
          It's a reasonable question. Endoscopic surgery, in many contexts, represents genuine
          technological progress. In laparoscopic abdominal surgery, in arthroscopy, in many
          neurosurgical approaches — the camera enables visualization that would otherwise require
          massive incisions.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-6">
          But does this logic apply to <strong>midface lifting</strong>? That's where we need to
          examine the specifics rather than assume "more technology = better."
        </p>

        <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-accent-500 pl-6 my-8 italic text-xl">
          "The question isn't 'which has more technology?' It's 'which provides better
          visualization, control, and outcomes for this specific procedure?' Those are different
          questions."
          <footer class="text-base not-italic mt-2">— Dr. Robério Brandão</footer>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Comparison Table -->
