  </section>

  <!-- The Physics of Visualization -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-ivory">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-serif text-primary-900 mb-8">The Physics of Visualization</h2>

      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-warmGray">
        <p class="mb-6">
          Understanding why Direct Vision can outperform camera-based systems requires examining the
          physics involved:
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-serif text-primary-900 mt-10 mb-4">
          Stereoscopic vs Monocular Vision
        </h3>

        <p class="mb-6">
          Human eyes provide <strong>stereoscopic (3D) vision</strong> through binocular disparity — each
          eye sees a slightly different angle, and the brain fuses these into depth perception. This is
          how we judge distances, identify planes, and navigate three-dimensional space.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-6">
          Standard endoscopes provide <strong>monocular (2D) vision</strong>. You're looking at a
          flat screen, not the actual surgical field. Depth cues must be inferred from shadows,
          tissue movement, and instrument position — a learned skill that takes significant
          practice.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-6">
          3D endoscopes exist but add cost, complexity, and still don't match the natural depth
          perception of direct binocular vision through surgical loupes.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-serif text-primary-900 mt-10 mb-4">
          Latency and Real-Time Control
        </h3>

        <p class="mb-6">
          Any camera system introduces latency — the delay between light entering the camera and the
          image appearing on screen. Modern systems minimize this, but the delay exists. In
          microsurgery, even milliseconds matter.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-6">
          Direct Vision has <strong>zero latency</strong>. Light travels from tissue to your eye at
          approximately 299,792 km/s. What you see is happening now, not 10-50ms ago.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-serif text-primary-900 mt-10 mb-4">Tactile Integration</h3>

        <p class="mb-6">
          Perhaps most importantly, Direct Vision maintains the natural <strong
            >hand-eye-tactile loop</strong
          >. When you're looking directly at tissue while your hands work, vision and touch
          integrate seamlessly. You feel resistance, tissue density, vessel pulsation — and your
          eyes confirm what your hands sense.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-6">
          Endoscopic surgery partially disconnects this loop. Your hands are in one place, your eyes
          are on a screen, and the tactile feedback comes through extended instruments. Skilled
          endoscopists compensate, but the compensation is a workaround, not an advantage.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Cost Reality -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-white">
