              <span class="font-bold">Total Investment</span>
              <span class="font-bold">$1,600-5,000</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="p-8 bg-red-50 border-2 border-red-200 rounded-xl">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-red-800 text-xl mb-4">Endoscopic Setup</h3>
          <ul class="space-y-3 text-red-700">
            <li class="flex justify-between">
              <span>Endoscope camera + processor</span>
              <span class="font-semibold">$40,000-60,000</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex justify-between">
              <span>Monitor system</span>
              <span class="font-semibold">$15,000-25,000</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex justify-between">
              <span>Light source</span>
              <span class="font-semibold">$10,000-20,000</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex justify-between">
              <span>Instruments + scope</span>
              <span class="font-semibold">$20,000-40,000</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex justify-between border-t border-red-300 pt-3 mt-3">
              <span class="font-bold">Total Investment</span>
              <span class="font-bold">$85,000-145,000</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-warmGray">
        <p>
          This cost difference — <strong>approximately 30-90x</strong> — raises an obvious question: if
          Direct Vision provides equivalent or better visualization, where does the value of the endoscopic
          investment come from?
        </p>

        <p>
          For procedures where camera visualization is genuinely necessary (no line-of-sight
          access), the investment is justified. For midface lifting where Direct Vision is viable,
          the ROI calculation changes dramatically.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ Section -->
